article.description: Taj McWilliams-Franklin scored 20 points, including the game-winning layup with 2.3 seconds left, to lead the Connecticut Sun to a 68-66 victory over the Charlotte Sting in the opening game of their best-of-three WNBA Eastern Conference playoff series
article.headline: Sun rally from eight down in final minutes

images.name: McWilliams-Franklin_Taj_030828 vert inline
images.caption: Taj McWilliams-Franklin is averaging 18 points and shooting 63.2 percent from the field in the playoffs.

article.linkText: Sun queen: Taj hits game-winning layup
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- There was that play again. Taj
McWilliams-Franklin caught the ball on the high post, turned hard
inside and banked in a layup just seconds before time expired.

<photo1>As she had done twice before this season, McWilliams-Franklin
nailed the game-winner for the Connecticut Sun.

The latest heroics lifted Connecticut to a 68-66 victory over
the Charlotte Sting on Thursday night in the opening game of their
best-of-three WNBA Eastern Conference playoff series.

"To be in a position to help this team win, it's just an
awesome feeling," said McWilliams-Franklin, who had 20 points and
nine rebounds.

She scored eight points in the Sun's closing 10-2 run over the
final five minutes. She hit a 3-pointer and was fouled by Dawn
Staley with 1:45 left and converted the four-point play to pull
Connecticut within 66-64.

"The 3-point shot she made and got fouled was maybe the play
that turned the momentum for us," Sun coach Mike Thibault said.
"That was the play when our players believe they were going to
win."

Sun guard Shannon Johnson hit two free throws with 52 seconds
left to tie it.

Nykesha Sales, who finished with 11 points for Connecticut, came
up with the key defensive stop, blocking a jumper by Andrea
Stinson. Johnson won the scramble for the ball and called a timeout
for Connecticut, allowing the Sun to set up the winning play.
Initially, Thibault wanted McWilliams-Franklin to post up, but he
called a different play just as the huddle broke.

"It was a great call by Coach and she is great at finishing
those shots by either scoring or getting fouled," Sales said.

On the final play, McWilliams-Franklin took a pass from Johnson
and had a wide-open lane when Sting center Tammy Sutton-Brown
peeled off to guard Johnson, who ran a fake inside.

"I had to go out and act like the play wasn't for me. (Johnson)
cut hard and Tammy Sutton-Brown bit the cut and I penetrated. It
was a Hail Mary, but I went to a Catholic school," said
McWilliams-Franklin, a graduate of St. Edward's, a small college in
Texas.

Sales stole the inbounds pass to preserve the win.

Game 2 is Saturday at Charlotte. They split their regular season
series, 2-2, as each team took two games on its home floor,

"We're going home and we'll play well at home," Sting coach
Trudi Lacey said. "We had this one, but it just got away. If
nothing else, it will fire us up."

Staley led the Sting with 15 points, while Allison Feaster added
12.

The Sting led 33-28 at halftime, doing most of their damage from
the perimeter. Feaster had two of Charlotte's five first-half
3-pointers. She, Stinson and Staley each hit from behind the arc in
the opening five minutes.

Charlotte led by as many as six points in the closely contested
first half. The Sun managed to scratch out a couple of one-point
leads down the stretch on the strength of their inside game,
outscoring Charlotte 12-6 in the post.

Teanna McKiver, Charlotte's reserve center, injured her left
ankle in a scramble for a rebound late in the second half and did
not return.

The Sting were making their sixth postseason appearance. It was
the first postseason meeting between the teams.

The Sun, the former Orlando Miracle, were making only their
second postseason appearance since the franchise's first season in
1999. On the brink of disbanding seven months ago, the team was
purchased by the Mohegan Indian tribe and play their home games in
the tribe's Mohegan Sun Casino.

"You're a veteran so you have to play big, especially in the
big games," McWilliams-Franklin said. "It's the championship
every game for us, especially now. We want to establish something
here at the Sun."
